english:
  title: Edict on the Appointment of the Unified Monk-Administrator for the Avatamsaka Order
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: '...Thus, the reason the state establishes ranks and offices within the Buddhist order is this: when among the monks there appears one outstanding as a dragon or phoenix—whose virtue and reputation none dare contest—yet without a title to mark him, how would he differ from the common multitude? Therefore, one whose virtue merits the foremost seat is called the Chief Seat, and one whose virtue and renown unite and govern all monks is called the Unified Monk-Administrator. This is the highest selection among them. Though it began as a title to honor the Way, it holds no relation to worldly profit. Yet ranks and gradations exist among these offices, and so gradually it has come to resemble the court''s system of ranks and official appointments. Thus one must carefully discern the person before conferring such a post. The Master, as a dharma king, has long illuminated the Complete Teaching and been revered by the multitude. How could I grudge such a selection, when it brings blessing and benefit to the realm? ...'
  footnotes:
    - '首座 (Chief Seat): The highest rank among the regular Buddhist monastic hierarchy'
    - '僧統 (Unified Monk-Administrator): An administrative position overseeing all Buddhist monks, typically awarded to senior masters'
    - '圓敎 (Complete Teaching): A Buddhist theological concept referring to the perfect, all-encompassing teaching'
    - '法王 (Dharma King): An honorific title for an eminent Buddhist master'
